WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.400
Today I want to talk about a new package that I've been working on called vctrs and this

00:00:13.400 --> 00:00:20.360
associated idea of type stability, which basically means that ideally it should be easy to predict

00:00:20.360 --> 00:00:24.440
what type of thing your function returns.

00:00:24.440 --> 00:00:28.760
But before we get into that, I want to talk a little bit about the motivation in terms

00:00:28.760 --> 00:00:29.760
of some WATs.

00:00:29.760 --> 00:00:33.599
How many of you have heard of WAT before?

00:00:33.599 --> 00:00:40.240
Okay, WAT is like WAT or W-T-E-F, but even more surprising.

00:00:40.240 --> 00:00:46.639
And there's a really great talk at this URL that kind of created this term, talking about

00:00:46.639 --> 00:00:51.560
some of the really surprising things about Ruby and JavaScript, and so I'm going to show

00:00:51.560 --> 00:00:59.520
you some really kind of crazy stuff in R, and this is sort of the motivation.

00:00:59.520 --> 00:01:03.599
So I'm going to show you a little bit of code, so here I've got two factors, and I combine

00:01:03.599 --> 00:01:07.559
them together, and what do I get?

00:01:07.559 --> 00:01:09.800
What?

00:01:09.800 --> 00:01:13.599
You might hope that I get an A and a B in there, right, and hopefully maybe the output

00:01:13.599 --> 00:01:14.599
would be a factor.

00:01:14.599 --> 00:01:19.000
You probably did not expect to get two 1s out of that.

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:25.639
Or what happens if I take a date and a date time and combine them together?

00:01:25.639 --> 00:01:26.639
What?

00:01:26.639 --> 00:01:31.080
It took me a while to even kind of, like, figure out what was going on here, but this

00:01:31.080 --> 00:01:41.800
is a day, a date, and in the year 4,200,010, 937 on the 24th of January.

00:01:41.800 --> 00:01:43.120
Or what happens if you do the other thing?

00:01:43.120 --> 00:01:47.559
What happens if you combine a date time with a date?

00:01:48.120 --> 00:01:49.120
What?

00:01:49.120 --> 00:01:59.839
Again, we get the date time that I gave it, and I get this weird date in 1969.

00:01:59.839 --> 00:02:03.599
What happens if you even look at a date time the wrong way?

00:02:03.599 --> 00:02:11.600
So what happens if you take a date time and just concatenate it with nothing?

00:02:11.600 --> 00:02:14.080
You lose the time zone.

00:02:14.119 --> 00:02:17.720
Or what happens if you combine it with a literal nothing, a null?

00:02:17.720 --> 00:02:20.919
Oh, you get this random number.

00:02:20.919 --> 00:02:31.600
So I seriously hope that no one would argue that this behavior is correct.

00:02:31.600 --> 00:02:33.759
I think there's some kind of good reasons of this.

00:02:33.759 --> 00:02:38.119
There's not great reasons, but there's some accidents of history that have led us to this

00:02:38.119 --> 00:02:44.160
place where we can get some pretty surprising results from, like, pretty unsurprising data

00:02:44.160 --> 00:02:49.520
types and a pretty unsurprising operation, C.

00:02:49.520 --> 00:02:53.639
But so what's kind of� and what's even kind of worse about this is I've just shown you

00:02:53.639 --> 00:02:57.160
one function, but there's a bunch of other places we have to do this.

00:02:57.160 --> 00:03:00.360
You've got to take two vectors of different types and combine them together.

00:03:00.360 --> 00:03:06.279
You get this in unlist and R bind and if else and merge and a bunch of other places.

00:03:06.279 --> 00:03:10.880
And I don't mean to just pick on base R here, but tidyverse has exactly the same problem,

00:03:10.880 --> 00:03:16.399
that some functions for combining two vectors together do something different to other functions,

00:03:16.399 --> 00:03:20.720
which is clearly a really, really bad thing.

00:03:20.720 --> 00:03:25.520
And so kind of the motivation for this vectors package was to think about, well, like, what

00:03:25.520 --> 00:03:26.520
should we do?

00:03:26.520 --> 00:03:29.839
This is clearly crazy what currently happens.

00:03:29.839 --> 00:03:31.320
How can we do better?

00:03:31.320 --> 00:03:33.160
What should we do?

00:03:33.160 --> 00:03:39.399
And I think we can get some hint of that by looking at the rules for C, for concatenate,

00:03:39.399 --> 00:03:45.880
for atomic vectors, because the rules here are, like, pretty simple and pretty reasonable.

00:03:45.880 --> 00:03:50.440
And here I've kind of displayed them in, like, painful detail.

00:03:50.440 --> 00:03:52.720
If you've got a logical and logical, you get a logical.

00:03:52.720 --> 00:03:55.320
If you've got a logical and an integer, you get an integer.

00:03:55.320 --> 00:04:00.240
And if you just list them all out like this, it seems pretty complicated, but you can kind

00:04:00.240 --> 00:04:02.520
of display this in a table form, too.

00:04:02.520 --> 00:04:05.479
So if you've got a logical and a logical, you get a logical.

00:04:05.479 --> 00:04:09.440
If you've got a double and a character, you get a character.

00:04:09.440 --> 00:04:16.040
And if you stare at this table a little bit, you'll notice that it's actually symmetrical.

00:04:16.040 --> 00:04:18.160
And that's a really nice principle, right?

00:04:18.160 --> 00:04:22.679
Because it means, in this sense, it means it doesn't matter which order the arguments

00:04:22.679 --> 00:04:25.940
are, you're going to get the same type of output.

00:04:25.940 --> 00:04:29.559
And it means you've got, like, a lot less to, you've got less than half of the table

00:04:29.559 --> 00:04:31.200
to remember now.

00:04:31.880 --> 00:04:36.480
And that also means we can actually express it even more simply.

00:04:36.480 --> 00:04:42.040
We can express it as a, well, this is technically a tree.

00:04:42.040 --> 00:04:43.239
This is a very simple tree.

00:04:43.239 --> 00:04:44.880
It's a tree with no branches.

00:04:44.880 --> 00:04:48.160
I'll show you a tree with some branches a little bit later.

00:04:48.160 --> 00:04:53.799
But you can kind of, you can sort of work this tree by, if you've got, like, a logical

00:04:53.799 --> 00:04:57.920
and a double, say, you kind of follow the arrows until they meet up at a common place,

00:04:57.920 --> 00:05:00.200
which in this case is a double, right?

00:05:00.200 --> 00:05:04.320
So you can just put your finger on the two types and then follow the arrow from one to

00:05:04.320 --> 00:05:07.600
the other to know which type you're going to get.

00:05:07.600 --> 00:05:11.920
And so now this is a pretty simple summary of the rules that Bayes R pretty consistently

00:05:11.920 --> 00:05:15.959
applies to atomic vectors.

00:05:15.959 --> 00:05:21.480
And I think even if you've never been explicitly taught this, you've probably, like, kind of

00:05:21.480 --> 00:05:27.880
picked it up implicitly, because this rule is consistently applied.

00:05:27.880 --> 00:05:32.160
The problem with C, however, arises that when we start to get to these more complicated

00:05:32.160 --> 00:05:37.239
S3 vectors, which are built on top of these atomic vectors, that there aren't any kind

00:05:37.239 --> 00:05:39.200
of simple rules anymore.

00:05:39.200 --> 00:05:44.640
So when we get to factors and dates and date times and data frames, things start to get

00:05:44.640 --> 00:05:51.640
more complicated, and it is exceedingly difficult to elucidate the complete set of rules.

00:05:51.640 --> 00:05:56.519
So figuring out what the rules should be, at least in my opinion, is the goal of this

00:05:56.519 --> 00:06:01.799
vectors package, and I kind of, I don't know, the thing I like most about this package is

00:06:01.799 --> 00:06:08.160
possibly the logo, which is very Tron inspired.

00:06:08.160 --> 00:06:12.839
So the goal of vectors is to kind of figure out these principles kind of like once and

00:06:12.839 --> 00:06:18.320
for all to apply them everywhere, and the goal in some sense of vectors is a little

00:06:18.320 --> 00:06:23.920
bit weird, because I think if vectors are successful, that there becomes this consistent

00:06:23.920 --> 00:06:28.239
set of rules, the package itself becomes invisible.

00:06:28.239 --> 00:06:34.119
So my goal is that you should never, ever have to know that this package exists.

00:06:34.119 --> 00:06:37.640
But I want to talk, but unless you're a package developer, unless you start to dive into the

00:06:37.640 --> 00:06:42.540
details, we can start to now learn this pretty simple theory.

00:06:42.540 --> 00:06:49.640
And the basic idea of vectors is to take that very simple tree we had before, that line,

00:06:49.640 --> 00:06:52.119
and basically kind of turn it into a forest.

00:06:52.119 --> 00:06:54.140
So again, the same principles apply.

00:06:54.140 --> 00:06:58.760
If you want to combine two types of vector, you put your finger on each one, and then

00:06:58.760 --> 00:07:00.760
you follow the arrows.

00:07:00.760 --> 00:07:05.000
So you will notice, however, that this is not like a tree, this is a forest.

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:06.920
Some of the things are not connected.

00:07:06.920 --> 00:07:12.160
You cannot put your finger on factor and double and find any way to go between them.

00:07:12.160 --> 00:07:14.679
And I think this is really, really important.

00:07:14.679 --> 00:07:18.320
There are some coercions that simply do not exist.

00:07:18.320 --> 00:07:23.239
It does not, there's no way that it makes sense to combine a factor and a date time

00:07:23.239 --> 00:07:28.160
together instead of trying to do something, trying to guess at what you mean.

00:07:28.160 --> 00:07:32.600
It's much safer to get an error that forces you to confront the fact that you've got a

00:07:32.600 --> 00:07:35.839
mix of weird data types.

00:07:35.839 --> 00:07:38.720
You have to deal with that yourself.

00:07:38.720 --> 00:07:41.600
So I'm going to do a little demo of this.

00:07:41.600 --> 00:07:48.799
Live demos are always risky, but this should be fairly safe.

00:07:48.799 --> 00:07:56.399
So I've got the vectors package loaded, and basically I'm going to show you this function

00:07:56.399 --> 00:08:00.720
called vec underscore C, which is basically the same as the C function you're familiar

00:08:00.720 --> 00:08:04.239
with from base R, but obeys this consistent set of rules.

00:08:04.239 --> 00:08:08.959
So if I get a logical and an integer together, or a logical and a double together, I'm going

00:08:08.959 --> 00:08:10.040
to get double.

00:08:10.040 --> 00:08:14.040
If I take a double and an integer, I get a double.

00:08:14.040 --> 00:08:16.440
These are the rules that you're already familiar with.

00:08:16.440 --> 00:08:19.239
You don't even have to think about them.

00:08:19.239 --> 00:08:23.359
It is a little bit stricter about coercing the character vectors.

00:08:23.359 --> 00:08:29.279
So if you try and combine a double and a character together, you get an error.

00:08:29.279 --> 00:08:33.599
This is unlike base R, where you can just combine these things that are a little bit

00:08:33.599 --> 00:08:38.239
different together, and R will just do it for you.

00:08:38.640 --> 00:08:44.520
So vectors is a little bit more strict in general, because it has this escape hatch.

00:08:44.520 --> 00:08:50.599
All of these vectors functions allow you to declare the desired prototype of the output.

00:08:50.599 --> 00:08:56.599
So here I can say, actually, I want the output to be a prototype, this character type.

00:08:56.599 --> 00:09:00.119
And I call this a prototype, because you don't give it a name of a type.

00:09:00.119 --> 00:09:02.359
You give it an example of a type.

00:09:02.359 --> 00:09:08.799
So here I'm saying, make sure the output looks like a empty character vector.

00:09:08.799 --> 00:09:10.200
And so I can do that.

00:09:10.200 --> 00:09:16.840
And now, instead of implicitly coercing vectors to a common type, here we're going to explicitly

00:09:16.840 --> 00:09:19.799
cast to the type that we have provided it.

00:09:19.799 --> 00:09:24.599
So now we have this consistent way that you can say, I want to make sure the output is

00:09:24.599 --> 00:09:29.799
a character vector, and it will either be a character vector, or you will get an error.

00:09:29.799 --> 00:09:35.320
You will never get any other type of output when you call the function in this way.

00:09:35.320 --> 00:09:38.799
So again, we get the same kind of similar property with factors.

00:09:38.799 --> 00:09:40.020
We can combine them together.

00:09:40.020 --> 00:09:42.340
We always get a factor back.

00:09:42.340 --> 00:09:49.320
Now note, the order in which we combine the factor is important, because the levels are

00:09:49.320 --> 00:09:50.320
different.

00:09:50.320 --> 00:09:57.559
So if I combine A and B first, the levels are A and then B. If I combine B, then A,

00:09:57.559 --> 00:09:59.679
the levels are in the opposite order.

00:09:59.760 --> 00:10:04.520
So it turns out it's kind of not possible to be completely symmetric, because the only

00:10:04.520 --> 00:10:08.799
option here, if I wanted to be completely symmetric, is I think I'd have to sort the

00:10:08.799 --> 00:10:13.520
factor levels, which seems like a really, really bad idea and not very useful.

00:10:13.520 --> 00:10:20.159
So the thinking behind vectors is kind of a combination of philosophy and pragmatics.

00:10:20.159 --> 00:10:24.520
There are some things that would just be maybe kind of philosophically more beautiful or

00:10:24.520 --> 00:10:28.880
more pure, but pragmatically would just cause you a bunch more pain when trying to use this

00:10:29.080 --> 00:10:30.080
in your code.

00:10:30.080 --> 00:10:35.039
And so vectors tries to kind of balance those things, tries to steer you in a direction

00:10:35.039 --> 00:10:40.080
of greater safety, of greater strictness, of this idea of type stability, which I'll

00:10:40.080 --> 00:10:47.039
come back to shortly, and away from just kind of always working, doing whatever happens.

00:10:47.039 --> 00:10:50.340
So the same thing works with ordered factors.

00:10:50.340 --> 00:10:54.359
If you try and combine a factor and an ordered factor, you're going to get an error.

00:10:54.359 --> 00:10:59.320
You can combine factors and characters, or again, you've always got this escape hatch.

00:10:59.320 --> 00:11:04.440
You can say, if there isn't an automatic coercion that exists, I can always say, I want the

00:11:04.440 --> 00:11:06.919
output to be of this type.

00:11:06.919 --> 00:11:12.000
So again, vectors is going to be more likely to give you errors than base R is, because

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:16.640
it gives you the standard way of resolving those errors by explicitly declaring the type

00:11:16.640 --> 00:11:19.520
of output that you want.

00:11:19.520 --> 00:11:24.119
And again, with dates and datetimes, this is like basically the most boring demo ever,

00:11:24.119 --> 00:11:30.400
because it just does what I think any reasonable person would expect it to do.

00:11:30.400 --> 00:11:33.919
If you combine dates and datetimes together, you don't get crazy dates, far, far in the

00:11:33.919 --> 00:11:34.919
future or far in the past.

00:11:34.919 --> 00:11:41.320
And if you just concatenate a single vector with itself, then the time zone's unchanged.

00:11:41.320 --> 00:11:45.520
And then when you try and combine different things in base R, I kind of showed you a few

00:11:45.520 --> 00:11:46.520
of these before.

00:11:46.520 --> 00:11:50.320
But if you combine a factor and a datetime, you get an integer.

00:11:50.320 --> 00:11:55.159
But if you combine a datetime and a factor, you get a datetime, a date with a weird date.

00:11:55.159 --> 00:12:01.359
I mean, vectors just always gives you an error.

00:12:01.359 --> 00:12:04.840
And again, then there's always this other kind of one last escape hatch.

00:12:04.840 --> 00:12:10.440
Like what happens if you really do want to combine a datetime and a factor into a single

00:12:10.440 --> 00:12:11.440
vector?

00:12:11.440 --> 00:12:15.840
Well, you can always fall back to a list, because a list in R can contain anything else.

00:12:15.840 --> 00:12:19.239
So we can always say, make sure the output is a list.

00:12:19.239 --> 00:12:30.039
And we'll just combine all these things together.

00:12:30.039 --> 00:12:37.200
So the underlying idea behind vectors is this idea of type stability, which I'm still trying

00:12:37.200 --> 00:12:41.919
to figure out how to express, to articulate as clearly as possible.

00:12:41.919 --> 00:12:43.640
But I think there's this principle.

00:12:43.640 --> 00:12:48.599
The way I sort of think about it is, like, when you're reading R code, what you are actually

00:12:48.599 --> 00:12:53.679
doing is running that R code in your internal mental model of R.

00:12:53.679 --> 00:12:59.840
And obviously, your internal mental model of R is much, much simpler than the real thing.

00:12:59.840 --> 00:13:03.799
But I think in your internal mental model of R, one thing that's really useful to think

00:13:03.799 --> 00:13:06.440
about is the type of each variable.

00:13:06.440 --> 00:13:10.400
And I notice that when I read other people's code, when I'm reviewing pull requests, for

00:13:10.400 --> 00:13:15.280
example, if I read the code and I look at a variable and I have no idea what type of

00:13:15.280 --> 00:13:20.520
variable that is, I don't know if it's a list or a character or a data frame, that code

00:13:20.520 --> 00:13:24.559
just feels very dangerous to me, because I cannot accurately predict what's going to

00:13:24.559 --> 00:13:25.679
happen.

00:13:25.679 --> 00:13:30.440
So the first principle of type stability is that the output type should only depend on

00:13:30.440 --> 00:13:33.260
the types of the inputs.

00:13:33.260 --> 00:13:39.000
And so one kind of violation of this in base R is the if else function.

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:41.719
So here I've got three calls to if else.

00:13:41.719 --> 00:13:44.280
The first argument is always logical.

00:13:44.280 --> 00:13:46.640
The second argument is always an integer.

00:13:46.640 --> 00:13:49.599
The third argument is always a character vector.

00:13:49.599 --> 00:13:55.719
And yet, depending on the value of the logical vector, the output could be a logical vector,

00:13:55.719 --> 00:14:00.119
it could be a double vector, it could be a character vector.

00:14:00.119 --> 00:14:04.479
And I think this is an undesirable property, because when you read code that involves if

00:14:04.479 --> 00:14:09.840
else, it makes it hard to know what type of output you're going to get.

00:14:09.840 --> 00:14:13.919
And again, I don't want to say, like, the tidyverse is perfect, it's far from perfect.

00:14:13.919 --> 00:14:20.559
Deply if else actually is equally annoying, but in the opposite direction, it's too strict,

00:14:20.559 --> 00:14:23.960
which forces you, if you want to insert a missing value, to know about all of these

00:14:23.960 --> 00:14:28.200
different types of missing values that you should never be forced to confront, and it's

00:14:28.200 --> 00:14:30.559
pretty annoying.

00:14:30.559 --> 00:14:35.400
The second principle is that if you're just combining a bunch of vectors or your argument

00:14:35.400 --> 00:14:39.840
has dot, dot, dot in it, your function has dot, dot, dot in it, the order of the inputs

00:14:39.840 --> 00:14:42.559
should not affect the output type.

00:14:42.559 --> 00:14:46.960
So I kind of showed you an example of this already, lots of examples of this with C,

00:14:46.960 --> 00:14:53.859
but ideally, the order in which you supply arguments to C should not affect the output.

00:14:53.859 --> 00:14:57.239
This is the idea that gave us that symmetry in the table.

00:14:57.239 --> 00:15:01.320
This makes predicting the output much, much, much simpler, because there's just a much

00:15:01.320 --> 00:15:05.880
smaller set of rules that you need to remember and internalize.

00:15:05.880 --> 00:15:11.039
And again, the goal here is not that you should ever have to explicitly memorize the rules,

00:15:11.039 --> 00:15:15.799
but hopefully by having this small set of reasonable and consistent rules, you will

00:15:15.799 --> 00:15:22.919
just come to learn them over time, and when you predict, when you guess, your naive guess

00:15:22.919 --> 00:15:29.200
about what a function will return should just be more accurate from the get-go.

00:15:29.200 --> 00:15:36.440
And then the final principle is almost so obvious that you shouldn't have to say it,

00:15:36.440 --> 00:15:41.960
and that is ideally, there should be one set of rules that is applied everywhere.

00:15:41.960 --> 00:15:46.840
So again, just to illustrate this, if you concatenate two factors together, you get

00:15:46.840 --> 00:15:52.880
an integer vector, but if you put those factors together in a list and then you unlist them,

00:15:52.880 --> 00:15:55.799
you will get a factor as you expected.

00:15:55.799 --> 00:16:00.840
So the fact that we have these inconsistencies just makes it hard to build up that accurate

00:16:00.840 --> 00:16:03.520
mental model, and it gets confusing.

00:16:03.520 --> 00:16:09.520
And I think there's sort of both this first-order effect that when you look at some code, you're

00:16:09.520 --> 00:16:12.799
like, oh, I don't know what this is going to return, but you also get the second-order

00:16:12.799 --> 00:16:17.239
effect that's even worse, that over time you sort of get this learned helplessness.

00:16:17.239 --> 00:16:21.840
You're like, I have no idea, I've been burned so many times before, I've got no idea what

00:16:21.840 --> 00:16:25.280
this is going to return, so I'm just not even going to try to guess, which I think

00:16:25.280 --> 00:16:28.159
is even more harmful.

00:16:28.159 --> 00:16:32.520
Now vectors does a bunch of other things, which I want to talk about briefly.

00:16:32.520 --> 00:16:38.080
Max really, really, really wants to give me the gong if I talk too long, so I don't want

00:16:38.080 --> 00:16:45.239
to make him too happy, but I want to talk about briefly these other parts of vectors.

00:16:45.239 --> 00:16:50.200
So one thing that I have recently discovered about data frames is that you can have a column

00:16:50.359 --> 00:16:56.559
of a data frame that is itself a data frame.

00:16:56.559 --> 00:17:02.559
And this is supported in base R, so here I'm creating a data frame, and then I'm making

00:17:02.559 --> 00:17:06.280
a column of that data frame that is itself a data frame.

00:17:06.280 --> 00:17:11.920
And you may ask yourself, well, why on earth would I ever do such a crazy thing?

00:17:11.920 --> 00:17:16.680
And I don't really have a great answer for you right now, but it seems pretty cool and

00:17:16.680 --> 00:17:20.680
like it might be useful, and so I thought it would be worthwhile to kind of work through

00:17:20.680 --> 00:17:26.199
all of the implications of that, and so that's one of the things that vectors does.

00:17:26.199 --> 00:17:31.880
Another thing very closely related to type stability is this idea that I call size stability.

00:17:31.880 --> 00:17:37.319
This is basically kind of the recycling rules of base R that you know if you combine a vector

00:17:37.319 --> 00:17:42.920
that is, when you combine two vectors of different lengths, there are these things in R called

00:17:42.920 --> 00:17:45.800
the recycling rules, which determine what's going to happen.

00:17:45.920 --> 00:17:50.839
I think those recycling rules are like a really good idea, but they have two flaws.

00:17:50.839 --> 00:17:55.439
The first flaw is that they will recycle, like if you combine a vector of length 2 and

00:17:55.439 --> 00:18:00.719
a vector of length 3, it will combine the vector of length 2 like a non-integer number

00:18:00.719 --> 00:18:04.680
of times, which I think is just a little bit too clever in most cases.

00:18:04.680 --> 00:18:09.040
And the other problem with the recycling rules, if you sort of start looking into them with

00:18:09.040 --> 00:18:13.560
a fine-tooth comb, you discover there isn't actually one set of recycling rules, there's

00:18:13.560 --> 00:18:17.839
actually like four sets of recycling rules that are very subtly different.

00:18:17.839 --> 00:18:23.760
So again, the idea of these kind of size stable functions is given the sizes of the inputs,

00:18:23.760 --> 00:18:28.400
you should be able to easily predict the size of the output.

00:18:28.400 --> 00:18:33.079
And then finally, the last feature in vectors is that we should have easier ways to create

00:18:33.079 --> 00:18:36.339
new types, new vector classes.

00:18:36.339 --> 00:18:40.800
So if you have ever tried to create a new type of vector in R, something like a factor

00:18:40.800 --> 00:18:43.800
or a date time, currently it's really painful.

00:18:43.800 --> 00:18:47.640
You need to understand a lot about the S3 object system.

00:18:47.640 --> 00:18:52.000
You've got to define methods for a lot of different generics.

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:56.560
Vectors also provide some support so that when you create new types of vectors, there's

00:18:56.560 --> 00:18:58.160
some clear documentation.

00:18:58.160 --> 00:19:02.099
If you want your vector to do this, you need to define these methods.

00:19:02.099 --> 00:19:06.900
If you want it to do that, you need to define these other methods.

00:19:06.900 --> 00:19:10.979
So if you want to learn more about vectors, two places to start are the vectors website

00:19:10.979 --> 00:19:18.780
itself, which has a lot of very detailed information about how that package works, which is not

00:19:18.780 --> 00:19:23.060
that accessible right now, but will hopefully get a little easier to understand over time.

00:19:23.060 --> 00:19:27.859
And then there's also more information about it in the vectors chapter of advanced R.

00:19:27.859 --> 00:19:34.180
One of the big goals of the tidyverse in 2019 is to thoroughly integrate these ideas.

00:19:34.180 --> 00:19:39.780
One last thing before I go, and that is if you are interested in working with RStudio

00:19:39.780 --> 00:19:44.339
on the tidyverse or Shiny team, we are having an internship program again this year.

00:19:44.339 --> 00:19:48.260
We'll have about 10 interns in paid positions over the summer.

00:19:48.260 --> 00:19:52.439
You have to be able to work in the U.S., so we're trying to work on international students

00:19:52.439 --> 00:19:53.439
next year.

00:19:53.439 --> 00:19:57.819
If you would like to find out more or apply, go to this URL.

00:19:57.819 --> 00:19:58.819
Thank you.

00:19:58.900 --> 00:20:00.900
Thank you.

00:20:00.900 --> 00:20:02.900
Thank you.

00:20:02.900 --> 00:20:04.900
Thank you.

00:20:04.900 --> 00:20:06.900
Thank you.

00:20:06.900 --> 00:20:16.339
We probably have time for one or two questions while we switch over mics.

00:20:16.339 --> 00:20:21.160
So if you got a question, wave your hand, and someone will throw a mic to you or at

00:20:21.160 --> 00:20:22.160
you.

00:20:22.160 --> 00:20:23.160
Yes.

00:20:23.160 --> 00:20:24.160
Hi.

00:20:24.160 --> 00:20:26.439
This is really exciting, but I think one of the things I always struggle with when we

00:20:26.439 --> 00:20:30.000
talk about these things is I feel like in kind of just like the community, we don't

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:34.500
have like a great concrete definition of what we're talking about when we say type in terms

00:20:34.500 --> 00:20:37.880
of like, does the metadata matter for the type, or are we just talking about like built-in

00:20:37.880 --> 00:20:38.880
types?

00:20:38.880 --> 00:20:39.880
Are we talking about classes?

00:20:39.880 --> 00:20:40.880
Yeah.

00:20:40.880 --> 00:20:41.880
Right?

00:20:41.880 --> 00:20:44.040
Like, are there like resources or like some kind of like common language we're developing

00:20:44.040 --> 00:20:45.479
for like what we mean by this stuff?

00:20:45.479 --> 00:20:46.479
Yeah.

00:20:46.479 --> 00:20:50.719
So that's another aspect of the vectors package is this idea of the prototype, which I just

00:20:50.719 --> 00:20:52.459
kind of glossed over here.

00:20:52.459 --> 00:20:58.020
But the goal of that is to provide this sort of consistent and concrete discussion of what

00:20:58.020 --> 00:21:00.939
we actually use, what I actually mean when I say type.

00:21:00.939 --> 00:21:05.939
I think like 90% of the time, just your sort of everyday understanding is enough, but yeah,

00:21:05.939 --> 00:21:08.859
we need a very concrete and precise definition.

00:21:08.859 --> 00:21:18.780
And that my goal is to supply that in the vectors package.

00:21:18.780 --> 00:21:20.300
We could do one more quick question.

00:21:20.300 --> 00:21:21.300
Thank you.

00:21:21.300 --> 00:21:26.420
So I just thought that the factors were internally represented as integers, yet they were on

00:21:26.420 --> 00:21:29.900
separate trees in the three trees that you mentioned.

00:21:29.900 --> 00:21:34.260
So is it not the case that they're integers in their normal representation, or is there

00:21:34.260 --> 00:21:36.099
something else that's different there?

00:21:36.099 --> 00:21:41.739
So they are internally represented as integers, but you as a data scientist should never be

00:21:41.739 --> 00:21:44.939
forced to grapple with that.

00:21:44.939 --> 00:21:49.619
Like the fact that when you concatenate them together, that underlying implementation is

00:21:49.660 --> 00:21:51.780
exposed, I think is a really bad thing.

00:21:51.780 --> 00:21:56.780
And so the idea of vectors is to hide you from that.

00:21:56.780 --> 00:21:59.939
So I noticed there's a bunch of people coming in for Jenny's talk.

00:21:59.939 --> 00:22:05.619
So if there is a seat next to you, please move towards the middle, or do not be surprised

00:22:05.619 --> 00:22:08.099
if the tidyverse suddenly stops working on your computer.

